4vr.title: Subjective probability
4vr.clickbait: Probability is in the mind, not in the environment.  If you don't know whether a coin came up heads or tails, that's a fact about you, not a fact about the coin.
4vr.text:
[summary:  What does it *mean* to say that a fair coin has a 50% probability of landing heads?

Subjective probabilities are a tool for quantifying your personal uncertainty about the world. Imagine flipping a coin and slapping it against your wrist. It's already landed either heads or tails. The fact that you don't know whether it's heads or tails is a fact about _you,_ not a fact about the coin. Ignorance is in the mind, not in the world. But what, exactly, is in your mind? Your mind is representing the coin, and you're unsure about which way the coin came up. Those probabilities, represented in your brain, are your subjective probabilities. [+1bv] is concerned with the formalization, study, and manipulation of subjective probabilities, and through probability theory, it is possible to learn quite a bit about how to manage our _own_ uncertainty so as to make our beliefs about the world more accurate.]

What does it *mean* to say that a flipped coin has a 50% probability of landing heads?

There are multiple ways to answer this question, depending on what you mean by "probability". This page discusses "subjective probabilities," which are a tool for quantifying your personal uncertainty about the world.

Imagine flipping a coin and slapping it against your wrist. It's already landed either heads or tails. The fact that you don't know whether it's heads or tails is a fact about _you,_ not a fact about the coin. Ignorance is in the mind, not in the world. But what, exactly, is in your mind? Your mind is representing the coin, and you're unsure about which way the coin came up. Those probabilities, represented in your brain, are your subjective probabilities. [+1bv] is concerned with the formalization, study, and manipulation of subjective probabilities, and through probability theory, it is possible to learn quite a bit about how to manage our _own_ uncertainty so as to make our beliefs about the world more accurate.

If probabilities are simply subjective mental states, what does it mean to say that probabilities are "good," "correct," "accurate," or "true"? This is one of the key subjects in probability theory. While it is quite difficult to say what set of beliefs is "completely true" (due, in part, to the fact that humanity does not yet know everything), probability theory describes ways to attach belief-states to reality in such a way that the more the belief-state interacts with reality, the more accurate its beliefs get. For example, your beliefs about whether or not it's cloudy interact with the clouds in the sky by means of your retina (mediated by light), and your brain is set up such that when light that came from the sky above you hits your retina, your beliefs about whether or not it's cloudy up there get more accurate.

In other words, while subjective probabilities are subjective, the laws that govern them are objective, and those laws tell us quite a bit about good and bad ways to maintain a belief state and respond to observations in a way that makes those beliefs more accurate. For this reason, subjective probabilities are a useful subject both for those who study human reasoning (because _we_ are physical systems that maintain a belief state and update it in response to observations), and those who study artificial intelligence. It's also an important topic of study for those who have a particularly strong need for accurate beliefs, such as truth-seekers and stock traders.

For an introduction to the basic laws of probability theory (and what they imply about how to use observations to update beliefs), refer to Arbital's [1zq guide to Bayes' rule].
